channel.title: Spring JIRA
channel.description: This file is an XML representation of an issue

item.title: [SPR-9208] application context created within java web start application triggers many http requests for non existing resorces
item.description:
Desktop application (swing client) is executed via web start. While application context is instantiated application performs many (122 times) http get requests for resources which don't exist. This of course has huge impact on time that is needed to application startup based on you network connection.

Here is a sample of access log (each entry is requested multiple times which in total for one time application execution gives 122 requests to the server):
127.0.0.1 - - [07/Mar/2012:15:07:24 +0100] "GET /neo-web/webstart/org.springframework.aspects.jar HTTP/1.1" 404 952 "-" "Java/1.7.0_03"
127.0.0.1 - - [07/Mar/2012:15:07:28 +0100] "GET /neo-web/webstart/org.springframework.beans.jar HTTP/1.1" 404 952 "-" "Java/1.7.0_03"
127.0.0.1 - - [07/Mar/2012:15:07:31 +0100] "GET /neo-web/webstart/org.springframework.core.jar HTTP/1.1" 404 952 "-" "Java/1.7.0_03"
127.0.0.1 - - [07/Mar/2012:15:07:36 +0100] "GET /neo-web/webstart/org.springframework.aspects.jar HTTP/1.1" 404 952 "-" "Java/1.7.0_03"
127.0.0.1 - - [07/Mar/2012:15:07:42 +0100] "GET /neo-web/webstart/org.springframework.web.jar HTTP/1.1" 404 952 "-" "Java/1.7.0_03"
127.0.0.1 - - [07/Mar/2012:15:07:51 +0100] "GET /neo-web/webstart/org.springframework.context.jar HTTP/1.1" 404 952 "-" "Java/1.7.0_03"

This is reproducible every time application is executed via webstart (javaws http://localhost:8080/neo-web/webstart/launch.jnlp). It can be reproduced only in java web start environment because there is JNLPClassLoader involved which indirectly causes jars lookup on the backend server.

I enclosed stacktraces on which you can see class lookups and then calls to the servers. In stacktrace2 - stacktrace3 I noted parameter which was used in method invocation JNLPClassLoader
JNLPClassLoader(ClassLoader).loadClass(String) line: 356 <----------- parameter is org.springframework.beans.factory.aspectj.AbstractInterfaceDrivenDependencyInjectionAspectBeanInfo --------->

The stacktrace1 is different than stacktraces 2-5 as the source of class loading is different. The latter (2-5) are pretty the same for most calls to the server (they differ only with different classes to be loaded)

status.description: A resolution has been taken, and it is awaiting verification by reporter. From here issues are either reopened, or are closed.

comments.comment:
Issue is caused by wrong jar name in index.list (details in https://jira.springsource.org/browse/SPR-6383)

as a quick fix, I corrected affected files (so the name of jar file is equal to the 3rd line of index.list) for following jars (spring-aspects-3.1.1.RELEASE.jar,spring-beans-3.1.1.RELEASE.jar,spring-web-3.1.1.RELEASE.jar,spring-context-3.1.1.RELEASE.jar). This is improvement, because instead of 122 requests I have 4:
127.0.0.1 - - 04/04/2012:17:16:09 +0200 "GET /neo-web/webstart/spring-aspects-3.1.1.RELEASE.jar HTTP/1.1" 200 54982 "-" "Java/1.6.0_31"
127.0.0.1 - - 04/04/2012:17:16:13 +0200 "GET /neo-web/webstart/spring-beans-3.1.1.RELEASE.jar HTTP/1.1" 200 623255 "-" "Java/1.6.0_31"
127.0.0.1 - - 04/04/2012:17:16:13 +0200 "GET /neo-web/webstart/spring-web-3.1.1.RELEASE.jar HTTP/1.1" 200 580644 "-" "Java/1.6.0_31"
127.0.0.1 - - 04/04/2012:17:16:13 +0200 "GET /neo-web/webstart/spring-context-3.1.1.RELEASE.jar HTTP/1.1" 200 890925 "-" "Java/1.6.0_31"

But this is still a problem, cause these jars are downloaded every time I run my application. This gives ca 2.2MB every launch of application, which is significant for poor connections (customers have to wait until these jars are downloaded)

As another quick fix I removed the index.list for problematic jars. This solved the problem. There is no extra requests to server. Rerunning application doesn't cause any requests to the server, so application gets fired immediately.

I have small update to 1st quick fix, the case when you want to fix index.list. There has to be match between resource name in app.jnlp and 3rd line in index.list. As an example consider following entries in jnlp file:

<resources>
<jar href="spring-core.jar" version="3.1.1.RELEASE" />
<jar href="spring-beans.jar" version="3.1.1.RELEASE" />
<jar href="spring-context.jar" version="3.1.1.RELEASE" />
<jar href="spring-web.jar" version="3.1.1.RELEASE" />
<jar href="spring-aspects.jar" version="3.1.1.RELEASE" />
</resources>

This means that spring-core.jar/META-INF/INDEX.LIST looks like following:
JarIndex-Version: 1.0

spring-core.jar
org
org/springframework
org/springframework/core
org/springframework/core/annotation
.....

so this has to be true -> jar.href equals index.list.3rdLine

I tested this for version based download protocol, but I guess it should also work for other download protocols
See resolution comments at SPR-6383

Solution for projects using maven(webstart-maven-plugin) to create webstart appliaction.
Remove INDEX.LIST file from spring jars that causes classloading problems:

  1. Unpack bugged spring dependencies with filter that excludes INDEX.LIST
  2. Pack fixed dependencies and copy it to jnlp work directory
  3. Sign excluded jars
  4. Exclude fixed dependencies from jnlp generation plugin.
  5. Add excluded jars to template.vm
    and after all call webstart plugin

I use spring.version pom property for spring-framework versioning

<properties>
 
  <!-- property added to template.vm - properties containing dots ('.') might not be passed properly -->
 
  <springVersion>${spring.version}</springVersion>
 
</properties>

STEP 1 - maven-dependency-plugin unpack bugged jars to 'dependency-fixed-jars'

<plugin>
 
<groupId>org.apache.maven.plugins</groupId>
 
<artifactId>maven-dependency-plugin</artifactId>
 
<version>2.4</version>
 
<executions>
 
  <execution>
 
    <id>unpack</id>
 
    <phase>package</phase>
 
    <goals>
 
      <goal>unpack</goal>
 
    </goals>
 
    <configuration>
 
      <artifactItems>
 
        <artifactItem>
 
          <groupId>org.springframework</groupId>
 
          <artifactId>spring-core</artifactId>
 
          <version>${spring.version}</version>
 
          <type>jar</type>
 
          <overWrite>true</overWrite>
 
          <outputDirectory>${project.build.directory}/dependency-fixed-jars/spring-core-${spring.version}</outputDirectory>
 
        </artifactItem>
 
        <artifactItem>
 
          <groupId>org.springframework</groupId>
 
          <artifactId>spring-context</artifactId>
 
          <version>${spring.version}</version>
 
          <type>jar</type>
 
          <overWrite>true</overWrite>
 
          <outputDirectory>${project.build.directory}/dependency-fixed-jars/spring-context-${spring.version}</outputDirectory>
 
        </artifactItem>
 
        <artifactItem>
 
          <groupId>org.springframework</groupId>
 
          <artifactId>spring-beans</artifactId>
 
          <version>${spring.version}</version>
 
          <type>jar</type>
 
          <overWrite>true</overWrite>
 
          <outputDirectory>${project.build.directory}/dependency-fixed-jars/spring-beans-${spring.version}</outputDirectory>
 
        </artifactItem>
 
        <artifactItem>
 
          <groupId>org.springframework</groupId>
 
          <artifactId>spring-web</artifactId>
 
          <version>${spring.version}</version>
 
          <type>jar</type>
 
          <overWrite>true</overWrite>
 
          <outputDirectory>${project.build.directory}/dependency-fixed-jars/spring-web-${spring.version}</outputDirectory>
 
        </artifactItem>
 
      </artifactItems>
 
      <excludes>META-INF/INDEX.LIST</excludes>
 
    </configuration>
 
  </execution>
 
</executions>
 
</plugin>

STEP 2 - copy-maven-plugin packs fixed dependencies and copy them to 'jnlp'(working directory for jnlp plugin)
http://evgeny-goldin.com/wiki/Maven-copy-plugin

  <plugin>
 
    <groupId>com.github.goldin</groupId>
 
    <artifactId>copy-maven-plugin</artifactId>
 
    <version>0.2.5</version>
 
    <executions>
 
      <execution>
 
        <id>create-archive</id>
 
        <phase>package</phase>
 
        <goals>
 
          <goal>copy</goal>
 
        </goals>
 
        <configuration>
 
          <resources>
 
            <resource>
 
              <targetPath>${project.build.directory}/jnlp/spring-core-${spring.version}.jar</targetPath>
 
              <directory>${project.build.directory}/dependency-fixed-jars/spring-core-${spring.version}</directory>
 
              <pack>true</pack>
 
            </resource>
 
            <resource>
 
              <targetPath>${project.build.directory}/jnlp/spring-context-${spring.version}.jar</targetPath>
 
              <directory>${project.build.directory}/dependency-fixed-jars/spring-context-${spring.version}</directory>
 
              <pack>true</pack>
 
            </resource>
 
            <resource>
 
              <targetPath>${project.build.directory}/jnlp/spring-beans-${spring.version}.jar</targetPath>
 
              <directory>${project.build.directory}/dependency-fixed-jars/spring-beans-${spring.version}</directory>
 
              <pack>true</pack>
 
            </resource>
 
            <resource>
 
              <targetPath>${project.build.directory}/jnlp/spring-web-${spring.version}.jar</targetPath>
 
              <directory>${project.build.directory}/dependency-fixed-jars/spring-web-${spring.version}</directory>
 
              <pack>true</pack>
 
            </resource>
 
          </resources>
 
        </configuration>
 
      </execution>
 
    </executions>
 
  </plugin>

STEP 3 - maven-jarsigner-plugin sign fixed jars, because in webstart-maven-plugin we exclude them

  <plugin>
 
    <groupId>org.apache.maven.plugins</groupId>
 
    <artifactId>maven-jarsigner-plugin</artifactId>
 
    <version>1.2</version>
 
    <executions>
 
      <execution>
 
        <id>sign</id>
 
        <goals>
 
          <goal>sign</goal>
 
        </goals>
 
      </execution>
 
    </executions>
 
    <configuration>
 
      <keystore>myKeystore</keystore>
 
      <storepass>myPass</storepass>
 
      <alias>pluginsigner</alias>
 
      <archiveDirectory>${project.build.directory}/jnlp</archiveDirectory>
 
    </configuration>
 
  </plugin>

STEP 4 - in webstart-maven-plugin we exclude fixed jars 

  <plugin>
 
    <groupId>org.codehaus.mojo.webstart</groupId>
 
    <artifactId>webstart-maven-plugin</artifactId>
 
    <version>1.0-beta-2</version>
 
    <executions>
 
      <execution>
 
        <phase>package</phase>
 
        <goals>
 
          <goal>jnlp-inline</goal>
 
        </goals>
 
      </execution>
 
    </executions>
 
    <configuration>
 
      <!--REQUESTS FIX STEP 4-->
 
      <dependencies>
 
        <!-- Note that only groupId and artifactId must be specified here. because of a limitation of the Include/ExcludesArtifactFilter -->
 
        <excludes>
 
          <exclude>org.springframework:spring-core</exclude>
 
          <exclude>org.springframework:spring-context</exclude>
 
          <exclude>org.springframework:spring-beans</exclude>
 
          <exclude>org.springframework:spring-web</exclude>
 
        </excludes>
 
      </dependencies>
 
 
 
      <!-- JNLP generation -->
 
      <jnlp>
 
        <inputTemplate>src/jnlp/template.vm</inputTemplate>
 
        <outputFile>myApp.jnlp</outputFile>
 
        <mainClass>my.package.Main</mainClass>
 
      </jnlp>
 
 
 
      <sign>
 
        <keystore>myKeystore</keystore>
 
        <storepass>myPass</storepass>
 
        <alias>pluginsigner</alias>
 
        <verify>false</verify>
 
      </sign>
 
    </configuration>
 
  </plugin>

STEP 5 - in template.vm we add excluded dependencies manually

<?xml version="1.0" encoding="$encoding"?>
 
<jnlp
 
    spec="$jnlpspec"
 
    codebase="$jnlpCodebase"
 
    href="$outputFile">
 
  <information>
 
#if($project.Name)
 
    <title>$project.Name</title>
 
#end
 
#if($project.Organization.Name)
 
    <vendor>$project.Organization.Name</vendor>
 
#end
 
#if($project.Url)
 
    <homepage href="$project.Url"/>
 
#end
 
#if($project.Description)
 
    <description>$project.Description</description>
 
#end
 
#if($offlineAllowed)
 
    <offline-allowed/>
 
#end
 
  </information>
 
#if($allPermissions)
 
  <security>
 
     <all-permissions/>
 
  </security>
 
#end
 
  <resources>
 
    <j2se version="$j2seVersion"/>
 
     $dependencies
 
    <jar href="spring-core-${springVersion}.jar"/>
 
    <jar href="spring-context-${springVersion}.jar"/>
 
    <jar href="spring-beans-${springVersion}.jar"/>
 
    <jar href="spring-web-${springVersion}.jar"/>
 
  </resources>
 
  <application-desc main-class="$mainClass"/>
 
</jnlp>

@urbanq, thanks for the write-up. Indeed, per SPR-6383, this is just what we did for Spring 3.1.2: removing INDEX.LIST from Spring jars. So if you're running into this issue, and can update to 3.1.2+, then you're already good to go.
